African Safari 2009
I love this picture because it captured an amazing moment during our trip. The local guides named this lion "Tripod" because he sustained a serious injury to his rear leg in a fight some months earlier and he still walks with a severe limp. Despite this, they believe he will survive. I see the proud determination in his expression here.

Here's one of the famous documentary star Machli, aka 'The Lady of the Lake' and the 'Crocodile Killer is the most photographed wild tiger in the world. At 16 years old, she's Ranthambore's oldest tiger, but with just half a canine left, she may not survive much longer in the wild.

The Asiatic lion's habitat is dry scrub land and open deciduous forest. These lions were once found across northern Africa, south west Asia and northern Greece. Now there are only around 523 (census 2015) left in the wild and all of them are in or around the Gir Forest National Park, Gujarat, India

description:
It was our second round in the forest.....earlier in the afternoon just after reaching we did our first park round through canter and saw 2 tigers (T19 Krishna and cub). It was a separate sighting and the cub was fast asleep. T19 was as usual acting like super mom searching for food and was about to attack a spotted deer but gave up as the deer was not within its attack radius..
The second park round was supposed to be more fruitful since it was in the morning. We were in Gypsies, a group of 6 persons per Gypsy, so less noise and a smoother drive aided in optimum eye level photography. We were allotted Zone No. 1 which is supposed to be good and area of Noor and her 2 male cubs. We drove looking for birds and other things. Suddenly i noticed something and I asked the driver to stop the car - It was  a Striped Hyena - one of the rare / uncommon sightings and even odd for that particular time in the morning. Our guide / driver was losing his cool & was showing signs of being irritated as we were stopping for each and every bird and for so called "common" things. Suddenly we heard an alarm call of Spotted Deer as well as Hanuman Langurs. We stopped and waited for a few minutes.However, the alarm call diminished soon and the reason could have been a male tiger /tigress who could have been sitting camouflaged by the tall grass. We drove further ahead and after some time we saw a bunch of gypsies standing near a rock wall. A cub was sitting on the cliff and watching us curiously. This was the junior cub of Noor ( we came to know about this eventually).... we parked our jeep and started shooting the "Male" cub, the fellow Jeep members whispered that there is another tiger cub behind the rock wall. This funny cub was running behind the Painted Spurfowl or the Langurs above. This was a "poser" male cub and was giving fantastic poses and with lots of facial expressions. Suddenly he vanished behind the rock and we all were disappointed.....but just after a gap of 5 minutes he re-appeared and sat on the top of the rock facing other side. Soon the second cub appeared and sat just in front of his brother but we could see only his ears and some portion of his head..
Soon this "cartoon" cub started running for the passing Hanuman Langurs and just appeared in front of our Jeep. We captured hundreds of his antics on camera . Somehow we were dreaming for the second cub to come forwards and sit next to his brother so that we can click "The Two Brothers" together. But the cub behind was not at all in the mood to move from his position. All of a sudden the first cub was very curious and watching intently behind our jeep. We were thinking that it must be his mommy returning to the cubs. This fellow was making funny faces but highly aware of his surroundings. We were also curious why the cub was so restless and alert. Soon he got up and started to climb on to the rock... which was just above us! and if by chance he jumped from there, he would have landed directly on our jeep! We all sat quietly and observed carefully.... carefully as he might jump on us but at the same time with the hope that we may get some good shots. Somehow one of the tourists in the back jeep saw a spotted  female deer approaching the lake next to our jeep. Now we all realised that "this " is the thing for which the cub was so restless and active. This was a learning curve for me ... that how a small cub (about 14/16 months old) can smell a prey from such a long distance. He started stalking on the rock itself..... but he was on the high rock at the right side... then down on the road we are in 3/4 jeeps... and then at the left side of our jeep (road) there was a small lake where the Spotted Deer was approaching for water. The cub started making faces and showed his hyperactive side. The deer approached slowly towards the water...now the second male also smelled the "prey" and stood up on the spot. The poor deer was unaware about the danger that awaited them at the paws of the two mighty predators. The deer started drinking water slowly... the second cub came forward and now he  was on the edge of the rock. The rock was approx 12/15 feet tall. He took some time and then he started crouching and stalking......all were mesmerized and engrossed with the act. Many fellow photographers were lost in the scene and forgot about the photography and were simply enjoying the thrill. I was quite focused 
and glued to the 1.5 centimeter viewfinder and never left the viewfinder as i wanted to catch the drama. Of course there were 5 jeeps in front of us so I was aware that we might miss the "hunt"but I was hoping for the best and concentrated on my "viewfinder" only though it was my maiden attempt to capture the kill in front of me. At that point of time my whole life was concentrated in that 1.5 cm viewfinder and of course for that Spotted Deer. Within a fraction of a second the second cub leaped from the rock and crossed the road in front of the jeeps and chased the deer. The deer sensed the danger and started running away helter skelter... but the cub was too fast and powerful and he smacked him with his mighty paw... the deer was thrown away just like a football... but the cub pounced on him again and pressed the deer on the ground and just sat there for many minutes.... just like a winner with the trophy... it might be his first ever individual hunt without the help of mother "Noor". The first cub, which also ran behind the deer as a backup plan, calmly went away and sat a few feet away from the kill and the trophy winning brother.... may be a tad upset as he missed his "kill". As the kill was pressed in the ground and was not visible due to a log and some bushes in front, we missed the feasting shots. We were only able to click pictures of the cub with his face painted in the deer's blood whenever he grasped the leg, neck and lifted the kill.
Camera trapped.

Cuiaba River,
near Porto Jofre,
Pantanal,
Brazil
15 August 2017

On August 16, we witnessed what has to rank with one of the most incredible wildlife experiences I’ve ever had. Cheryl and I were on a trip with 6 other nature photographers and our leader. We had been in the Pantanal area of Brazil for about a week with 5 days along the Cuiaba River near Porto Jofre, looking for Jaguars and other photo ops. Our daily routine was breakfast at 5:30 AM and we took off on boats from 6 till about 11AM, lunch at noon at the lodge, then on the boats again 3PM till dark. Our group has 3 boats so just 3 people per boat so plenty of room for photo gear, etc. Over several days we had seen 10-12 Jaguars. Some were very good photo ops, some poor photo ops, some just glimpsed. 

There are several lodges in the area and it is a popular place to visit for folks hoping to see Jaguars, so much like Yellowstone National Park, a crowd can gather when some significant wildlife is seen, but instead of car jams to see a Grizzly such as  Yellowstone, this can be boat jams for a jaguar. I have seen as many as 22 boats, 70-100 feet off shore with lots of people in each boat taking photos of a sleeping Jaguar. BUT…that is not the end of the story! We were often in more remote areas of the rivers and inlets and streams more or less on our own looking for birds, etc., so lots of times there are no other boats around. The boat drivers all have radios, so if a Jaguar is seen, other boats are informed. We move 20-25 miles up and down the river to explore, so many times other boats are not close enough to arrive while a Jaguar is in view. 

My limited Jaguar experience is that some are just sleeping and/or resting and mostly ignore the boats in the river. Others are walking though the edge of the forest near the river and when a boat becomes visible, the animal just vanishes back into the forest. This morning at about 7:30 AM our three boats were in an out-of-the way location, a mile or so apart. The boat I was in was photographing a Great Black Hawk when one of our other boats called us on the radio to say they had a Jaguar swimming in the river, apparently hunting, so we headed to that area. Apparently the Jaguar, with just its head visible, swam up to loafing Yacare Caimans and pounced onto a caiman which was about 6 or so feet long. The Jaguar and the caiman thrashed in the water with the Jaguar biting into the skull of the caiman. That is about the time our boat arrived, after the Jaguar had mostly subdued the caiman, but the caiman was still thrashing about. The Jaguar was up against a high dirt bank, still mostly in the water with a firm grip on the skull of the caiman and the Jaguar was not letting go. It was very dark and under heavy foliage and vines so I was shooting at 4000 and 6400 ISO but that was my only choice. Eventually the Jaguar was able to work itself and its prize away from the vines and it drug the caiman out of the water and up the dirt bank and eventually back into the forest to enjoy its catch beyond the curious and amazed eyes of the human observers. The caiman was as large or larger than the Jaguar. All I have to say is that a mature Jaguar is an incredibly powerful predator and watching this whole 15 minute episode is something I’ll not forget. What a beast!

This entire series was shot from a boat, perhaps 40 feet off the bank with a Canon EOS 7D Mark II and a Canon 100-400 IS lens in case anyone is interested.


Cuiaba River,
near Porto Jofre,
Pantanal,
Brazil
16 August 2017

Macho adulto.
Fotografado na Amazônia mato grossense, na Fazenda Dona Iris, município de Cotriguaçu.
É absolutamente impossível descrever um dos momentos mais esperados e espetaculares da minha vida!!!!
Na ocasião, contava com a agradável companhia do meu grande amigo Vitor Torga Lombardi.
Era por volta das 10 horas da manhã e nós estávamos conduzindo o nosso inventário de avifauna na margem esquerda do rio Juruena, nesse momento nossa atenção estava totalmente voltada para as mais altas árvores acompanhando a movimentação de um grande bando misto de aves que passava. 
Um faixo de luz solar incidia num canto da pequena estrada que nos abria caminho em meio aquela imensidão verde. Ao olharmos subitamente para aquele ponto, vimos um dourado reluzindo como ouro e contrastando com os vários tons de verde ao fundo. Forçamos os nossos olhos e então nos demos conta de que estávamos, frente a frente, a menos de 15 metros (!!!!), com um casal de onças-pintadas, o maior felino das Américas.
Foi indescritível, chocante, um verdadeiro misto de emoções! 
A fêmea logo sumiu no sub-bosque escuro, já o grande macho, em posição meio arqueada, olhava fixamente para nós, encarado-nos, olho a olho.
Tive a oportunidade de observá-lo rapidamente através das lentes do meu binóculo e ao tentar captar uma imagem do imponente macho, olhando fixamente para nós, tomado pela grande emoção do momento, acabei me enrolando todo com a máquina que havia ficado presa em alguma parte do meu colete. Ao conseguir liberar o equipamento e obter posição para fazer o disparo, o grande macho já seguia o seu curso de volta, rosnando, para o interior sombrio da floresta.
Juntaram-se a nós os outros dois integrantes da expedição, Márcio Schenck (Geógrafo) e Polaco (nosso guia mateiro). 
Após uma rápida conversa, nos mantivemos coesos e decidimos contar com o auxílio da técnica de play-back e pagar pra ver no que ia dar!
Rapidamente tratei de tocar (apenas uma vez) a faixa contendo o esturro da onça-pintada presente na coleção "Sounds of Neotropical Rainforest Mammals" e passados poucos segundos escutamos a resposta enfurecida do grande macho, esturrando altíssimo, bem do nosso lado! 
Ele estava muito, muito próximo, camuflado em meio a vegetação e nós não conseguíamos vê-lo. Caminhamos por cerca de uns 800 metros seguindo a estrada e de tempos em tempos ouvíamos os resmungos do grande felino e então nos demos conta de que ele nos seguia camuflado por entre a vegetação.
Não querendo mais abusar da sorte, decidimos voltar em direção ao carro, que estava parado alguns quilômetros para trás.
Foi um momento marcante e inesquecível que será para sempre lembrado com muita emoção.
Certamente foi um tanto quanto insano fazer o playback , mas como disse anteriormente, foi irresistível e uma oportunidade única! Com certeza, não testarei minha sorte numa outra oportunidade e eu não aconselho ninguém a repetir isso! Tem outra questão também, na ocasião, eramos quatro caboclos e muito provavelmente, apesar do bicho ter ficado extremamente nervoso, em resposta ao playback, creio que também estava muito intimidado com a nossa presença. Agora, meus amigos, se eu estivesse sozinho por ali, certamente, teria corrido no melhor estilo FORREST GUMP!

Serengeti National Park,
Tanzania
24 October 2018

Another one of those "National Geographic" observations which we were lucky to have. We came around a corner of some rocks and found a lioness with three cubs late in the afternoon resting on a large flat rock. We spent an hour there until it was too dark to take any images. She was a very patient mother with these little ones crawling all over her, biting her tail and her ears, etc. It was very special to see!

Serengeti National Park,
Tanzania
24 October 2018

I have another story to tell on this series of images. We left our camp just after 6 AM and about 1/2 mile from camp found a lioness in a tree with a male lion camped out at the base of the tree. The lioness did not look very comfortable, but she seemed to try to do her best to find a comfortable position. After 20 or 30 minutes she finally came down to the ground. There was still very little light and I had not been using a fast shutter speed while the lioness was in the tree. If I had known what was about to happen I could have made adjustments, but I failed to anticipate the action. When the female came out of the tree she started to walk away. The male came up behind her and tried to mount her. She wheeled away and snarled and roared at the male (image 6). The male kept coming at her and she launched at him and we had about 15 seconds of a roaring, raging battle. Most of the lions we had seen the previous week or so had been snoozing, etc., and we never heard a sound from them....but here was roaring that seemed to shake our vehicle...we were only 40 or so feet away from this pair. The 20th Century Fox roaring lion on the beginnings of movies is a wimp at roaring compared to the display by these two. I have included the shots I took of this encounter, but they are not sharp since my shutter speed was only 1/200 second....but you will be able to see the action. Finally the male backed off....and slunk away dejected.

Serengeti National Park,
Tanzania
25 October 2018

The end of another day on the endless plains of the Serengeti...a Leopard rests on a distant rock at sunset. Last image taken right over the top of the leopard showing the sunset. Just another day at the office.

Las huellas son derechas; si se observa con cuidado la pisada de la mano (la que está a la derecha) se puede ver que el dedo anular está fuera de lugar; es decir, que esta individuo tenía un dedo "chueco" y sus huellas se podían diferenciar de las de otros jaguares. Survival of physically disabled animals in the wild is near to impossible. But this was the first time when i observed a physically disabled leopard cub who is surviving yet. She is a female and adult cub now. I am observing her since she was a little. She got some physical injuries in her one front leg. This made her leg weak thus she cannot walk properly. But she amazed me when she reached her adulthood and separated from her mother. This is a perfect exception for survival of the fittest.

description: I was watching some very clear and very fresh Puma/Jaguar tracks, when out of the corner of my eye, I saw some movement. And sure enough... right in front of me was a Jaguar! The animal saw me as well and immediately started to move away from me. Not running, but definitely making haste, looking over its shoulder once or twice. As in previous cases like this, it took me valuable moments to realize what I was seeing, followed by another bit of wasted time for me to realize that I had a camera around my neck! So by the time I turned on the camera, the animal was about to disappear in the undergrowth. I didn't even use the viewfinder, just aimed and pressed the shutter, lo and behold.... I actually managed to get the back of the animal in the picture!

description: Taken through the windscreen with camera on Auto.  This sighting set the seal on a wonderful 5 days in the Eastern Cape

According to our park ranger, who knows all the tigers of this small park, this cub is almost three years old and about to be pushed out by its mama. There was no sign of mama nearby the evening.

Not the same cat as: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/66280545

Reportedly child of this female: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/66283701

Older tiger "cub" keeping cool in a shallow pool. He was startled by a tourist on the hillside behind him, riding an elephant instead of a jeep; elephant safaris promise closer observations, but this tiger didn't get that memo and took off when the sound of breaking branches came too near.

Not the same cat as: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/66280544

Reportedly child of this female: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/66283701

description: Wildcamera

Отпечатки лап тигра.
В вечернее время предыдущего дня (24 июня) проводили наблюдения за глухими кукушками и услышали несколько раз рык. На следующее утро (25 июня) на дороге, по которой мы возвращались вечером, увидели следы проследовавшего за нами тигра (протяженность следовой дорожки 0.5 км).
З июля снова встретились с тигром и записали рык на диктофон. Зверь был встречен в том же месте, где рычал в прошлый раз. Во время записи звук удаляется, так как зверь стал перемещаться вверх по склону.

description: I was watching birds as usual. On the way back to my home, I came face to face with this leopard. Leopard immediately fled back. At that time I was too surprised and it was too quick and too close - about 12 feet apart. I waited near the bush hoping it would come back. After 2 minutes leopard came to the same spot and moved towards the small water body.
Mother & cub in a sheltered dry riverbed. While we watched them from our safari vehicle, momma Leopard had to fight off a hungry Hyena to protect her cub---an amazing sight to behold!

description: Panthera leo melanochaita (Southern Lion). Photographed at Tarangire National Park, Tanzania on 30 October 2021.

When we arrived at the observation this leopard cub was finishing breakfast on a gemsbok carcass prepared by the mother. The sibling was in the tree next to the carcass. 
Having finished, the cub groomed itself in catlike fashion, then basked in the morning sun also displaying catlike curiosity. Eventually, it moved away from the carcass allowing the sibling to get down to feed. After staying in the background for 16 minutes, the cub walked away allowing the sibling to continue feeding.
See link where the sibling fed on the carcass.

This is a cub in a litter of two that fed on a gemsbok carcass provided by the mother. The sibling fed first – see https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/102418014. The sibling sat in the background for 16 minutes before moving off. The cub fed on the carcass for 34 minutes before it moved off.

description: Canon

Boro -- the dominant one of two brothers (on the right in the photos of both together). Both are sons of Patricia, the dominant female in the area, who returned to the area after she took them far away when they were mature. There is some speculation that they will eventually become the dominant males in the area.

This female is Gagu - as you can see, she is still nursing the two small cubs she kept hidden from view. Individual
ID by local biologist Alyson M. based on spot pattern.
Cub #2, male son of Patricia, with his brother and mother, just before she killed a caiman in front of our boat.

This is Patricia, just before she caught and killed a caiman before our eyes. With her are her two male cubs, who are mostly grown and do not yet have individual names that I was able to discover.  Individual ID by local biologist Alyson M. based on spot pattern.
This is the male jaguar Dume, sleeping in the shade on a riverbank. He's about 10 years old and is not one of the area's dominant males.ID by Alyson M. based on forehead spot pattern.

Some of the images were taken during postmortem as shared here.

It was actually killed at Sar Banda(but I couldn't locate it on map) which is close to Fazal Banda in Tehsil Matta, Swat.

PS. The images are posted to understand this locally critically endangered species better for future studies.

tag_list: kill, feeding, eating, lion, Panthera leo melanochaita, Panthera leo, Felidae, Carnivora, mammal, fauna, Santawani pride, Santawani Camp, Okavango Delta, Botswana, lioness, female, cub, cubs, juvenile, Lion kill
description:
Even after an entire day of feeding, the cubs are still at it.  Our guide observed that the adult lions would feed and be done for the day, whereas the cubs just seemed to keep eating.

Meanwhile, an adult lioness stands guard.  The kill was near the boundary of the Santawani pride’s territory, and the neighboring Green Pan pride had gathered about a hundred meters away hoping for a meal.  There were more Santawani lionesses resting just off frame, but it seemed like the pride was upping its game by stationing one right in front.

tag_list: lion, Panthera leo melanochaita, Panthera leo, Felidae, Carnivora, mammal, fauna, Santawani pride, female, lioness, Santawani Camp, Okavango Delta, Botswana, territoriality, territorial defense, Defending the kill
description: The Santawani pride had killed a water buffalo that morning. The kill was near the boundary of their territory, and a lactating mother from the neighboring Green Pan pride was hoping for a meal, but two adult females from the Santawani pride advanced on her and sent her packing.  She retreated without argument and waited quietly for leftovers even as more of her pride gathered.

description:
Essa é uma daquelas histórias que se contar, ninguém acredita. Eu e o Mario estávamos passarinhando e aguardando anoitecer para irmos atrás das corujas e bacurais. Logo após as 18:30, no início da noite, o Mário me diz: "Raul, acho que vi um cachorro ali na frente...". E assim, a menos de 50 metros, não havia apenas uma, mas duas onças-pintadas nos observando. Tentei tirar as fotos mas por causa da falta de luz, a câmera não conseguia acertar sem deixar borrada e não tivemos tempo. Rapidamente, as duas onças pularam no lago e foram nadando até a outra margem. Ficando apenas a sensação indescritível de observar esses animais fantásticos na natureza e o aviso para os observadores de aves não olharem apenas para cima.
Conheça a Amazon Birdwatching e venha passarinhar em Porto Velho-RO!

A confirmed case of lion poaching by professional Sudanese poachers from South Darfur. Body parts of large cats of prey such as the Northern Lion and the African Leopard are currently fetching high prices in the east of the Central African Republic and there is a brisk trade. Outside actively managed protected areas such as the 24,300 km2 core zone of the Chinko Conservation Area, it must be assumed that large carnivores (>15 kg) are hunted and tracked intensively over large areas. Unorganized international transhumance makes it easier to access, find and transport large carnivores even in the most remote regions far from permanent settlements, roads or any human infrastructure.

description:
Jaguar, Onça, Onça-pintada - Panthera onca (female)
My favorite image of this female, which loved to wait for prey on this branch overhanging the river. We watched her for hours on two separate days. She had a beautiful cub accompanying her, and images will be posted later. She is one of the well-known jaguars of this area, friends and Internet searches suggest her name is "Medrosa". her cub (male) is Pantaneiro. This was in Encontro das Águas State Park (Parque Estadual Encontro das Águas).

How not to hunt a Gaur. 

Saved this for my 10,000th observation on INaturalist.

No tigers were (seriously) hurt. This sub-adult male tiger mock-attacked this Gaur before receiving a strong kick to the shoulder. The kick was so quick, I didn't realise it had happened until I checked the photos later, never mind that I had caught it on camera. Maybe he'll think twice before tackling a Gaur again!

description:
Jaguar, Onça, Onça-pintada - Panthera onca (male cub, "Pantaneiro")
That name refers to the local breed of cattle from the Pantanal, or perhaps to a resident of the Pantanal in general.
The male cub spent much of his time resting above his mother's hunting perch. Our guide Samuel said that females have to protect their cubs from aggressive males, which may kill them in order to mate with the female.
Other images show cub with its mother "Medrosa".

The bird got fairly close to the leopard hidden behind bushes, but then walked away, seemingly unaware of its presence, and the leopard made no attempt to pounce. She then walked backward, and then began to half-heartedly approach dwarf mongooses.

Este ejemplar fue observado en Centro Kichwa Rio Guacamayos, en una area de bosque húmedo tropical. Presenta un pelaje amarillo dorado con manchas negras en forma de rosetas. Es un animal solitario y de hábitos mayormente nocturnos, aunque puede estar activo en el día. Es un especie clave para el equilibrio del ecosistema, ya que controla poblaciones de otras especies. Su presencia es indicadora de buena salud del bosque.

description:
Leopard | Panthera pardus | तेंदुआ in Gir National Park

A great wildlife encounter in Gir National Park, Gujarat, India.

It was the first of our three safari runs into the park and the sun was just starting to set. We reached a straight section of road and were starting to pick up speed when Gajendra Singh, the co-guide on our tour, said "leopard" and indicated to the jeep driver to stop. The park-assigned driver and guide were locked in deep conversation, oblivious to the surroundings, and continued forward. We started yelling Leopard! Stop! and the park people hit the brakes. 

The Leopard was walking away from the road and I got the camera on it - AI Servo, Single Spot AF Point placed on its eyes, maximum frames per second - and just let go. For once the settings weren't bad, and things worked out pretty well. Talking to Gajendra afterwards he explained that he had picked up on the alarm call of a Grey Langur, went into high alert, and immediately located the Leopard. The big cat had been stalking one of the monkeys, but its presence had been detected and it was moving away back into the forest. We thought the moment was over.

The Leopard came back towards the road, slunk down, then rocketed forward to the right, its tail swinging back to the left. The monkey it was eyeing and after made it safely up a tree.

Everything happened very quickly, and I really had no good idea of what I had been able to secure with my camera. After the Leopard had retreated back into the forest I began checking the photos on the LCD screen and my eyes widened. Big thanks to Gajendra for reading the situation and finding the Leopard, Rob Hutchinson and Birdtour Asia for arranging and leading the expedition, and everyone behind Gir National Park.

The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) classifies Leopard as Vulnerable, its populations from Asia to Africa declining under the pressures of habitat loss and direct human persecution. They are doing well in the Gir Forest, however, even if they are not as easy to see and photograph as the local lions. Our jeep safari guide reiterated that good Leopard images were very, very hard to obtain, so I felt especially privileged.

Asiatic Lion | Panthera leo leo | शेर

Our experience with Asiatic Lion in Gir National Park was ultimately wonderful, but also complicated. 

The story starts at park HQ, where we are assigned by lottery a driver, guide and route. The idea is to distribute tourist pressure evenly throughout the protected area, and ensure chance, not favouritism, determines who works what zone.

The next step is to drive to the indicated park entry point and begin the safari. Searching for lions in Gir seems to consist of driving fast along the routes, hoping for a Lion to be on or by the road. On the afternoon of our fateful first of three trips into the park, we had photography success with one big cat and a few birds when we came across a perplexing roadside scene. Very briefly, there were some motorcycles, official jeeps and park staff loosely stationed about 300 metres back from the road. On the road itself several tourist safari jeeps had gathered and discussions ensued between the drivers and guides. Next, a line of jeeps and a private car moved quickly by heading in the direction we had come. A decision was made - something was up, and we would follow the crowd.

Catch! Safari jeeps are not allowed to turn around once in the park - you have to continue in the direction you have been assigned. Loophole! No rule against backing up.

Our driver placed the vehicle in reverse and off we went - at fairly high speed for about a kilometre and a half, following the convoy. Eventually we reached a line of jeeps parked on the road, with that same private car placed right in the middle. Off in the forest we could see three people widely spaced in a line moving through the trees. Then, ahead of them, a large shadowy shape. Jockeying for position, our jeep backed closer, and we peered more closely into the woods. Suddenly, there it was - Asiatic Lion, and then another, and another. What was going on? 

Turns out the people were trackers and they were herding the lions to the road where a VIP in the private car had been placed to ensure a successful big cat encounter. And successful it was, with the lions plopping down right beside the excited viewers. It was really good to see the lions, and they were very close, but there was something slightly surreal about the moment. So after getting a good look and a few photos we signalled to our guide and driver that it was okay to go. They were quite happy to depart the scene, as they were worried about checking out of the park before sundown.

We drove out alone, putting a fair distance between us and the crowd. With no other vehicles around, and contemplating our successful encounter, we looked up and saw our own Lion walking down a hill towards us. In the gathering dusk we stopped and began taking photos (see above).

From a distance the Lion strode down the hill and continued to walk towards our open jeep - closer and closer. Given the human/lion interaction we had seen earlier, we weren't concerned for our safety, but it was still a heart-pounding moment. This is one of the last images I obtained before the animal was too close for my lens. It ended up passing by maybe five metres off the back of our vehicle and continuing downhill, just as the line of other vehicles pulled up. An amazing encounter and great natural history moment. Hats off to the managers of Gir National Park who have successfully balanced protecting this endangered animal and maximizing opportunities for huge crowds of humans to see it.

The Asiatic Lion's range once stretched from the middle east to India but by the late 1800s it was almost completely exterminated by humans, with less than a dozen individuals left. A tiny population survived on a hunting reserve in Gujarat, India, and under careful protection numbers have grown steadily in and around what has become Gir National Park. In May 2015 the lion population was estimated at 523. In August 2017, the Asiatic Lion Census identified 650 wild individuals. It remains classified as Endangered on the IUCN Red List because of its small population size, but the situation can nonetheless by celebrated as a growing conservation success.

A final note - the animal is considered a lion subspecies (not a full species) having split off from the African form approximately 100,000 years ago.

Spotted resting on the rock until late evening. Later was seen grooming for a while and moving around. 
The first sighting was on 28 nov 2024(it's said they had been here always and  until they are spotted we feel they don't exist). Back then the sighting had disturbed quite a few in the apartment. 
This sighting too was spotted by someone whose balcony faces the forest. This time not on the usual rock. Also not many were excited as until now already 3 other spottings had been reported. Also by now people have understood that leopard is not interested in them 😂. 
Me and Priyanka followed the telegram message and reached 17th floor of the forest facing block. Could finally spot him. Not the usual rock where we have seen him 3 times earlier. 
Cloudy Plus late evening. Very little light. We managed to see him in better light for the first 5 minutes where he was mostly in resting mode. Later 15 minutes he was grooming himself thoroughly and walked up to the next rock and was seen watching down the hill. Post that was too dark to see anything else.
Pride of 9 lions about 25km from Satara in Kruger. Unfortunately the one lion was injured and had a broken foot. As we were returned we saw the wildlife vet go and help.

This was an exciting find. Someone in the apartment telegram group alerted about the leopard sighting. I was pretty late to chk the messages. But still managed to get a good 15 minutes show of this majestic animal. Observed him rolling over the rock and finally get up and walk down. This sighting was overall a chaos. Though the animal was deep into the forest yet many in the apartment started demanding that the animal needs to be relocated. It took a few weeks to make them understand that it's not a good plan. Thankfully the forest department did not obliged to such requests.
